.TH FORMAT-BYTES 1
.f1
.SH NAME
\fBformat\-bytes\fR \-\- Formats a number of bytes for human-readable output
.SH SYNOPSIS
\fBformat\-bytes\fR [\-\fBlpk\fR] [\fB\-d\fR \fIdecimal\-length\fR] [\fB\-f\fR \fIfile\fR] [\fIbytes\fR]
.SH DESCRIPTION
The \fBformat-bytes\fR utility takes a number of \fIbytes\fR either from a file, command line, or standard input, and formats them using the most reader-friendly unit of measurement.
.P
For instance, the following line yields a result of "4.4 MB" (or "4.4 MBs" if the \fB-p\fR option is set):
.P
   $ format-bytes 4358361
.P
If \fIbytes\fR is omitted, the program reads from standard input instead:
.P
   $ echo '4358361' | format\-bytes
.SH OPTIONS
.TP 12
\fB\-d\fR  \fInum\fR
Specifies maximum decimal length (\fInum\fR digits after the decimal point).
.TP 12
\fB\-f\fR  \fIfile\fR
Read bytes from \fIfile\fR's size instead of a specified amount.
.TP 12
\fB\-l\fR
Use long unit names ("Kilobytes" instead of "KB", etc).
.TP 12
\fB\-p\fR
Pluralises short units when necessary; useful only if \fB-l\fR is off.
Note that byte units will never be pluralised, so the program won't generate an uncomfortable-looking result like "480 Bs".
.TP 12
\fB\-k\fR
By default, \fBformat-bytes\fR strips redundant zeroes after the decimal point as a result of meeting a required decimal length (set by the \fB\-l\fR option).
Setting \fB\-k\fR overrides this behaviour so formatted values like "20 KB" will still be printed as "20.00 KB".
Be aware this also affects "partial" decimal values like "20.30 KB" (which would otherwise be formatted "20.3 KB" with this option off).
\.TP 12
\fB\-h, \-\-help\fR
Display this help and exit.
.SH EXAMPLES
.TP
\fBBasic usage:\fR
$ format\-bytes 1600           # 1.56 KB
.TP
\fBUse longer measurement units:\fR
$ format\-bytes \-l 1600        # 1.56 Kilobytes
.TP
\fBAdd pluralisation for short units (no effect if -l is set):\fR
$ format\-bytes \-p 1600        # 1.56 KBs
.TP
\fBRead a file's size instead:\fR
$ format\-bytes \-f README.md
